Feature: the canonical BC CLAUDE.md primer pins choice suppression so a BC picks the next inbox item by arrival order or ADR-013 dependency precedence and acts, without surfacing the choice to its session-lead

  lead-hdn3 (P1) — BC-side analogue of the lead primer's "Standing rule: choice
  suppression" (lead-primer.md §185). The prodding pattern observed on
  bc-shopsystem-templates was a procedural which-first question put to the session-lead
  ("which message would you like me to dispatch first, or shall I take them in order?").
  That question's answer follows from a default — arrival order, or ADR-013 dependency
  precedence when items depend on one another — so it is the BC's call, not the
  session-lead's. The canonical BC primer must pin that the BC does not surface the
  procedural which-item-first choice and instead picks by the named default and acts.
  This is package-data primer prose, not a per-shop hand-edit.

  PRE-AUTHORED — dispatch deferred (BC-reliability serialization behind stranded
  lead-6669). Architect to compute @scenario_hash and apply @bc / dispatch tag at
  assignment time; @lead_integration tag below is provisional pending placement decision.

